{{coord|40|44|57.5|N|73|58|11|W|display=title|type:landmark}} [[File:Issiah Wall RBP sunny jeh.jpg|thumb|325px|Isaiah Wall and stairs]]
'''Ralph Bunche Park''' is a small municipal public park in the [[Turtle Bay, Manhattan|Turtle Bay]] neighborhood of [[New York City]], on [[First Avenue (Manhattan)|First Avenue]] between [[42nd Street (Manhattan)|42nd]] and [[43rd Street (Manhattan)|43rd Street]]s. It was named in 1979 for [[Ralph Bunche]], the first African-American to win the [[Nobel Peace Prize]].<ref name="Historical Sign">{{cite web|url=http://www.nycgovparks.org/sub_your_park/historical_signs/hs_historical_sign.php?id=6514|title=Ralph Bunche Park – Historical Sign|work=[[New York City Department of Parks and Recreation]]|accessdate=2010-07-01}}</ref>
The park is across First Avenue from the [[United Nations headquarters]]. (This stretch of First Avenue is also known as "United Nations Plaza".) The granite staircase in the park's northwest corner leads to 43rd Street and the [[Tudor City]] apartments. It was built and dedicated in 1948 during construction of the U.N. headquarters and has the famous quotation from [[Book of Isaiah|Isaiah]] 2:4: "They shall beat their swords into plowshares, and their spears into pruning hooks; nation shall not lift up sword against nation, neither shall they learn war any more" incised into its wall. Known as the '''Isaiah Wall''', it was rededicated in 1975 and had the name "Isaiah" added under the final word.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ralph Bunche Park|url=http://www.nycgovparks.org/parks/ralphbunchepark/monuments/785|work=New York City Department of Parks and Recreation|accessdate=2012-08-17}}</ref> In 1981 the staircase was named the '''Sharansky Steps''' in honor of [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] dissident [[Natan Sharansky]].<ref name="Historical Sign" />
In the plaza in front of the Isaiah Wall is ''Peace Form One'', a stainless-steel [[obelisk]] 50 feet (15 m) high, erected in 1980. The sculptor, [[Daniel LaRue Johnson]] (b. 1938), was a personal friend of Bunche, and dedicated the sculpture to Bunche, who won the Nobel Peace Prize in 1950.<ref>{{cite book|last=Urquhart|first=Brian|authorlink=Brian Urquhart|title=Ralph Bunche: An American Odyssey|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-lsfETlobAkC|accessdate=2010-07-02|year=1993|publisher=W.W. Norton & Company, Inc.|location=New York|isbn=0-393-03527-1|page=458}}</ref>
Near the southern end of the park is a plaque, dedicated in 1990, which commemorates [[civil rights]] leader [[Bayard Rustin]].<ref name="Historical Sign" />
Because of its proximity to the United Nations, the peace theme of the Isaiah Wall and ''Peace Form One'', and Bunche's career as a peacemaker, the park is a popular site for demonstrations and rallies concerning peace and other international issues.<ref>{{cite news |title=From Tudor City, Protests Against Noisy Protesters |first=Bruce |last=Lambert |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1994/05/22/nyregion/neighborhood-report-east-side-from-tudor-city-protests-against-noisy-protesters.html |newspaper=The New York Times |date=May 22, 1994 |accessdate=2010-07-02}}</ref> In 1985 the park was dedicated as New York City's first Peace Park.<ref name="Historical Sign" /> The park covers less than a quarter of an acre (1,000 m²), however, so it cannot accommodate major gatherings.
